  "title": "Lichen planus",
  "body_html": "<div>Lichen planus is a skin disorder of unknown aetiology, most probably being immune mediated.<br /><br />Features<br /><ul><li>itchy, papular rash most common on the palms, soles, genitalia and flexor surfaces of arms</li><li>rash often polygonal in shape, 'white-lace' pattern on the surface (Wickham's striae)</li><li>Koebner phenomenon may be seen (new skin lesions appearing at the site of trauma)</li><li>oral involvement in around 50% of patients</li><li>nails: thinning of nail plate, longitudinal ridging</li></ul><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/ddd110b.jpg'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/ddd110.jpg'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'> <span style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;'>&copy; Image used on license from </span><a href='http://www.dermnet.org.nz'  target='_blank' style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;' >DermNet NZ</a></td><td align='right'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox lbmagglasslink' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/ddd110b.jpg'><img src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/css/images/mag_glass.png'/></a></td></tr></table></CENTER><br />Lichenoid drug eruptions - causes:<br /><ul><li>gold</li><li>quinine</li><li>thiazides</li></ul><br />Management<br /><ul><li>topical steroids are the mainstay of treatment</li><li>extensive lichen planus may require oral steroids or immunosuppression</li></ul><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/ddd111b.jpg'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/ddd111.jpg'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'> <span style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;'>&copy; Image used on license from </span><a href='http://www.dermnet.org.nz'  target='_blank' style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;' >DermNet NZ</a></td><td align='right'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox lbmagglasslink' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/ddd111b.jpg'><img src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/css/images/mag_glass.png'/></a></td></tr></table></CENTER><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/ddd112b.jpg'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/ddd112.jpg'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'> <span style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;'>&copy; Image used on license from </span><a href='http://www.dermnet.org.nz'  target='_blank' style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;' >DermNet NZ</a></td><td align='right'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox lbmagglasslink' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/ddd112b.jpg'><img src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/css/images/mag_glass.png'/></a></td></tr></table></CENTER></div>\n\n<div id=\"mybodylinks\"></div>\n\n<div id=\"mybodymedia\"></div>\n\n\n<div id=\"categorynum\">5</div>\n\n<div id=\"subcategorynum\">400</div>\n\n<div id=\"categoryname\">Pathology</div>\n\n<div id=\"subcategoryname\">Musculoskeletal and obstetrics</div>\n<div id=\"mybody\">\n\n<div id=\"body_content\">\nLichen planus is a skin disorder of unknown aetiology, most probably being immune mediated.<br /><br />Features<br /><ul><li>itchy, papular rash most common on the palms, soles, genitalia and flexor surfaces of arms</li><li>rash often polygonal in shape, 'white-lace' pattern on the surface (Wickham's striae)</li><li>Koebner phenomenon may be seen (new skin lesions appearing at the site of trauma)</li><li>oral involvement in around 50% of patients</li><li>nails: thinning of nail plate, longitudinal ridging</li></ul><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/ddd110b.jpg'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/ddd110.jpg'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'> <span style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;'>&copy; Image used on license from </span><a href='http://www.dermnet.org.nz'  target='_blank' style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;' >DermNet NZ</a></td><td align='right'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox lbmagglasslink' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/ddd110b.jpg'><img src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/css/images/mag_glass.png'/></a></td></tr></table></CENTER><br />Lichenoid drug eruptions - causes:<br /><ul><li>gold</li><li>quinine</li><li>thiazides</li></ul><br />Management<br /><ul><li>topical steroids are the mainstay of treatment</li><li>extensive lichen planus may require oral steroids or immunosuppression</li></ul><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/ddd111b.jpg'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/ddd111.jpg'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'> <span style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;'>&copy; Image used on license from </span><a href='http://www.dermnet.org.nz'  target='_blank' style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;' >DermNet NZ</a></td><td align='right'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox lbmagglasslink' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/ddd111b.jpg'><img src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/css/images/mag_glass.png'/></a></td></tr></table></CENTER><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net